{"source_key":"sha256-ff2c6fbafcafdaafd5b2baa6c15ec4e2","record_index":9,"record_hash":"sha256:047a3573044491133af8a9de2f24b962f883cc98b492eb7655284924ae3fc21f","timestamp":"2026-06-15T17:50:42.204Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"On macOS, the quickest way is with `smartctl` from `smartmontools`.\n\nInstall it if needed:\n\n```bash\nbrew install smartmontools\n```\n\nThen check your internal SSD:\n\n```bash\nsudo smartctl -a disk0\n```\n\nLook for one of these fields:\n\n```text\nData Units Written\n```\n\nor sometimes:\n\n```text\nTotal LBAs Written\n```\n\nFor Apple/NVMe SSDs, `Data Units Written` is usually the useful one. NVMe “data units” are 512,000 bytes each, so TB written is:\n\n```text\nData Units Written × 512000 / 1,000,000,000,000\n```\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nData Units Written: 123,456,789\n```\n\nThat equals:\n\n```text\n123456789 * 512000 / 1000000000000 = 63.2 TB\n```\n\nYou can calculate it directly with:\n\n```bash\nsudo smartctl -a disk0 | awk -F: '[REDACTED:path] Units Written/ {gsub(/[^0-9]/,\"\",$2); print $2 * 512000 / 1000000000000 \" TB\"}'\n```\n\nIf `disk0` is not your internal SSD, list disks first:\n\n```bash\ndiskutil list\n```\n\nOn many MacBooks, the internal SSD is `disk0`, but not always.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-15T17:50:42.204Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}